Communicated by:
ProMED

["Current Situation of Screwworm in Panama:

"Currently, the screwworm (NWS) remains limited to the presentation of cases in a fluctuating way in the so-called Biological Protection Barrier within the province of Darien, with some very sporadic detections in the province of Panama. In the last 5 years there were 242 cases of NWS, the highest number was in 2019 with 81 and the lowest of 8 cases in 2018. Only in 2021 positive samples were identified in the province of Panama within the perimeter of 8 kilometers of the limits with the province of Darien.

"The effective control and eradication measure are the release of the sterile insect, complemented by the other actions of surveillance on the farm, control of the mobilization of animals and the installation of ground dispersal cages. Field activities have been reinforced with personnel and equipment to deal with suspicious reports in a timely manner, leading to more effective controls with a minimum of impact on the producers involved. However, for the success of the program it is essential to maintain the awareness of the producers in doing their part: to check, inspect and heal the wounds, good livestock practices with responsibility, transport only healthy animals and continue with the immediate report of suspicious cases." (Source: Panama-US Commission for the Eradication and Prevention of Screwworm (COPEG) https://www.copeg.org/en/producer-resources/)

"Humans can be affected similarly to animals. The disease can quickly become debilitating if it affects the eyes, mouth, nasal, or frontal sinuses, or the ears." (Source: Spickler, Anna Rovid. 2015. Screwworm myiasis. Retrieved from https://www.cfsph.iastate.edu/Factsheets/pdfs/screwworm_myiasis.pdf). - Mod.CRD

